environmental_stressor: Forced participation in totoaba bladder fishing operations
  through debt bondage to cartel financiers
family_situation: Widow raising her daughter's child after her daughter died trying
  to escape cartel debt. Her son Miguel disappeared after refusing to fish for totoaba.
file_name: last_human.json
final_thought: She wonders if the last vaquita felt the same helpless rage she does
  - caught in nets meant for something else, dying for someone else's greed, in waters
  that were supposed to be protected.
last_days_scenario: 'María Elena sits in her panga at dawn, the homemade hydrophone
  her marine biologist father built crackling with static. Three years since the last
  vaquita clicks. The cartel''s fishing coordinator expects her quota of totoaba nets
  deployed by noon - nets with mesh size perfect for accidentally catching the world''s
  smallest porpoise. Her granddaughter Paloma asks why abuela cries when she checks
  the hydrophone each morning. "I''m listening for ghosts, mija," she whispers. The
  protected refuge exists on paper in Mexico City, but here in the Upper Gulf, only
  cartel boats patrol these waters. Like the vaquita, María Elena is endemic to this
  place - five generations of her family fished these waters. Like the vaquita, she
  has nowhere else to go. The debt trap tightens like gillnet mesh: fish illegally
  or lose her boat, her home, her granddaughter''s future. She''s collateral damage
  in an economic system that values totoaba swim bladders at $50,000 per kilogram
  in Chinese markets. Each morning she deploys the nets that killed the last wild
  mammals she ever loved, caught in a system designed to extract wealth, not sustain
  life. The hydrophone crackles. Empty water. Empty future.'
